709115f-b.text:
Fifth Avenue, east side,south from E. 67th (left, not seen) to 66th Streets. The vacant lot at the N.E. corner of the latter point was formerly the site of the Havereyer home (852 Fifth Avenue). An 11 story apartment house, stands opposite same and is at the S.S. corner. The 5 story private dwelling shown is No. 854 and is the home of Emily V. White. This set consists of 2 views photographed in a southeastward direction from the Central Park
side of the Avenue.
April 23, 1938.
Views 1 and 2
P.L. Sperr

709116f-a.text:
Fifth Ave., east side, south from (No. 854) a point midway between East 67th and 66th Streets and across the latter to 65th Street, showing 3 structures and a vacant lot occupying this area. From left to right these are: the home of Emily V. White, No. 854; the former site of the Havermeyer homes (N.E. corner of 66th Street); an 11-story apartment house, No. 845 Fifth Ave., (at the S.E. corner of 66th Street) and the Temple Emanu-El Congregation of New York at the N.E. corner of 65th Street. The latter occupies the site of the former John J. Astor home.
July 21, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.

709120f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, east side, north from E. 67th Street, showing private mansions that face Central Park and form what was formerly known as the "Gold Coast". Prominently shown is the Whitney home at the N.E. corner of E. 88th Street as viewed across the cleared site of the former Chas. T. Yerkes home. At the right appears a portion of the Thomas Fortune Ryan home.
April 23, 1938.
P.L. Sperr
